"""
2D Magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) Magnetic Reconnection -- a coronal-heating model
=============================================================================

A self-contained Python/Matplotlib simulation and visualisation of resistive
magnetic reconnection in a solar-coronal current sheet, and the plasma heating
that reconnection produces.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHY THIS MODEL? (the physics in one paragraph)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Sun's corona is ~1-3 million K, yet sits above a 5800 K photosphere; supplying
that heat against radiative + conductive losses is the "coronal heating problem"
[Klimchuk 2006].  Parker's nanoflare model [Parker 1972, 1988] proposes that
photospheric motions braid coronal magnetic field into thin CURRENT SHEETS that
repeatedly reconnect, converting stored magnetic energy into heat and bulk flows.
Magnetic reconnection [Sweet 1958; Parker 1957; Priest & Forbes 2000] is the
breaking and re-joining of field lines at an X-point, enabled by a small but
finite resistivity.  This script reproduces that mechanism in 2D: a current sheet
goes unstable to the resistive TEARING mode [Furth, Killeen & Rosenbluth 1963],
forms magnetic islands/plasmoids, drives Alfvenic outflow JETS, and dissipates
the released magnetic energy as Ohmic (eta*J^2) heat -- the coronal-heating
signature.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
GOVERNING EQUATIONS  (2D incompressible reduced resistive MHD)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Reduced MHD" [Kadomtsev & Pogutse 1974; Strauss 1976; Biskamp 2000, ch. 2-4] is
the standard low-beta, 2D model for reconnection.  In the (x, y) plane the in-
plane magnetic and velocity fields are written through a flux function psi and a
stream function phi.  This guarantees the field is EXACTLY divergence-free
(del.B = 0), the central numerical difficulty of MHD [Brackbill & Barnes 1980;
Toth 2000]:

    B = z_hat x grad(psi)   =>  Bx = -d(psi)/dy ,  By =  d(psi)/dx
    v = z_hat x grad(phi)   =>  vx = -d(phi)/dy ,  vy =  d(phi)/dx

The out-of-plane current density and vorticity are then scalar Laplacians:

    j = z_hat.(curl B) = laplacian(psi) ,   w = z_hat.(curl v) = laplacian(phi)

With the normalisation rho = mu0 = 1 (lengths in L, speeds in the Alfven speed
v_A, times in the Alfven time tau_A = L/v_A) and the Poisson bracket
[a,b] = (da/dx)(db/dy) - (da/dy)(db/dx)  (which equals the advective derivative,
since v.grad f = [phi, f] and B.grad f = [psi, f]):

    d(psi)/dt = -[phi, psi] + eta * laplacian(psi)             (induction / Ohm's law)
    d(w)/dt   = -[phi, w]   + [psi, j] + nu * laplacian(w)     (vorticity / momentum)
    d(T)/dt   = -[phi, T]   + eta*j^2 + nu*w^2 + kappa*lap(T)  (internal energy)

  * induction  : Faraday + resistive Ohm's law E = -v x B + eta*J  [Biskamp 2000].
                 eta is the magnetic diffusivity; S = v_A L / eta is the Lundquist
                 number.
  * vorticity  : curl of the momentum equation; the [psi, j] term IS the curl of
                 the Lorentz force J x B that accelerates the reconnection jets.
  * energy     : Ohmic (eta*j^2) + viscous (nu*w^2) dissipation heats the plasma,
                 exactly the irreversible heating bookkeeping of a resistive MHD
                 code such as Lare3D [Arber et al. 2001].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
NUMERICAL METHOD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
* Fourier PSEUDO-SPECTRAL spatial discretisation on a doubly-periodic box:
  derivatives are exact (multiplication by i*k), nonlinear products are formed in
  real space, with the 2/3-rule to remove aliasing errors [Orszag 1971; Canuto,
  Hussaini, Quarteroni & Zang 1988; Boyd 2001].
* INTEGRATING-FACTOR (exponential) RK4 time stepping: the stiff linear diffusion
  operators (eta,nu,kappa * k^2) are integrated EXACTLY via exp(-D k^2 dt), and
  the nonlinear advection by classic RK4.  This is the standard cure for stiff
  spectral PDEs and stays stable at large S [Cox & Matthews 2002; Kassam &
  Trefethen 2005; Trefethen 2000].
* Adaptive time step set by the Courant-Friedrichs-Lewy condition [CFL 1928].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
REFERENCE LIBRARIES (used as primary sources / building blocks)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
* PlasmaPy  -- plasmapy.formulary gives the coronal plasma parameters that
               normalise the run  [PlasmaPy Community 2024, JOSS 9, 6053].
* Astropy   -- astropy.units / .constants carry physical units & constants
               [Astropy Collaboration 2013, 2018, 2022].
* Lare3D    -- Warwick Plasma's Lagrangian-remap resistive-MHD code; its energy
               bookkeeping (Ohmic + viscous/shock heating -> internal energy) and
               div(B)=0 treatment guided this formulation [Arber et al. 2001].

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
REFERENCES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
[1]  Parker E.N. 1957, J. Geophys. Res. 62, 509  (Sweet-Parker reconnection)
[2]  Sweet P.A. 1958, IAU Symp. 6, 123           (Sweet-Parker reconnection)
[3]  Harris E.G. 1962, Nuovo Cimento 23, 115     (the Harris current sheet)
[4]  Furth, Killeen & Rosenbluth 1963, Phys. Fluids 6, 459   (tearing instability)
[5]  Kadomtsev & Pogutse 1974, Sov. Phys. JETP 38, 283       (reduced MHD)
[6]  Strauss H.R. 1976, Phys. Fluids 19, 134                 (reduced MHD)
[7]  Parker E.N. 1972, ApJ 174, 499; 1988, ApJ 330, 474      (nanoflare heating)
[8]  Orszag S.A. 1971, J. Atmos. Sci. 28, 1074               (2/3 de-aliasing)
[9]  Brackbill & Barnes 1980, J. Comput. Phys. 35, 426       (div(B)=0 problem)
[10] Canuto, Hussaini, Quarteroni & Zang 1988, "Spectral Methods in Fluid Dynamics"
[11] Biskamp D. 2000, "Magnetic Reconnection in Plasmas", Cambridge Univ. Press
[12] Priest & Forbes 2000, "Magnetic Reconnection: MHD Theory & Applications", CUP
[13] Arber, Longbottom, Gerrard & Milne 2001, J. Comput. Phys. 171, 151  (Lare)
[14] Birn et al. 2001, J. Geophys. Res. 106, 3715            (GEM reconnection challenge)
[15] Cox & Matthews 2002, J. Comput. Phys. 176, 430          (exponential integrators)
[16] Kassam & Trefethen 2005, SIAM J. Sci. Comput. 26, 1214  (ETDRK4)
[17] Klimchuk J.A. 2006, Solar Phys. 234, 41                 (coronal heating review)
[18] Loureiro, Schekochihin & Cowley 2007, Phys. Plasmas 14, 100703 (plasmoid instab.)
[19] Courant, Friedrichs & Lewy 1928, Math. Ann. 100, 32     (CFL condition)
[20] Astropy Collaboration 2022, ApJ 935, 167;  PlasmaPy Community 2024, JOSS 9, 6053

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OUTPUT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
* ``reconnection_coronal_heating.mp4`` (or ``.gif``) -- 4-panel animation
* ``reconnection_final_state.png``                   -- peak-reconnection figure
* ``reconnection_energy_history.png``                -- energy/heating budget

Run:  python mhd_reconnection_coronal_heating.py   (use --quick for a fast preview)
"""

from __future__ import annotations

